        <task>
          <p>
            Is <m>f</m> a one-to-one function?
            Why or why not?
          </p>
          <solution>
            <p>
              Yes, because if <m>f(z_1)=f(z_2)</m>
              (where <m>z_1=r_1e^{i\theta_1}</m> and <m>z_2=r_2e^{i\theta_2}</m>,
              and <m>\theta _1</m> and <m>\theta _2</m> are the Arguments of <m>z_1</m> and <m>z_2</m>,
              respectively),
              then <m>\ln r_1+i\theta_1=\ln r_2+i\theta_2</m>.
              Equating real and imaginary parts gives <m>\ln r_1=\ln r_2</m>,
              so <m>r_1=r_2</m>
              (because the function <m>\ln</m> is one-to-one).
              Also, <m>i\theta_1=i\theta_2</m>,
              so <m>r_1e^{i\theta_1}=r_2e^{i\theta_2}</m>, \ie, <m>z_1=z_2</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
